Title: Notes on debugging HotSpot’s JIT compilation
Description: Typically when you compile a Java program, it is first compiled into bytecode by a Java compiler. However, this bytecode is not optimized yet. In HotSpot (OpenJDK’s JVM) this instead happens at runtime, and is done by a JIT, a Just-In-Time compiler. This way of doing things allows the JIT to take maximum advantage of the conditions that the code is running in, such as hardware, and even to a certain degree the specific data that is fed into the program.

Title: Building an email to calendar LLM

Talk is cheap, show me the code

They do require action of some sort ($ \geq lowest\ priority$), but the action is due in the near future ($\leq highest\ priority$). I tend to skim over these emails, get a gist of what is required of me, mark them as unread and promise to get back to them later.
